<P>
PEPPERDINE BOOKS SCALIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Associate Justice Antonin Scalia of the U.S. Supreme Court will teach a 
three-week summer class next year at Pepperdine University's School of Law. 
</P>
<P>
The conservative justice became the youngest member of the nation's high court 
when he was appointed by then President Ronald Reagan in 1986. Scalia, 52, 
previously served as a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of 
Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
Scalia follows in the steps of Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who taught a 
constitutional law course at the university three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
University officials said Scalia's class will focus on constitutional issues. 
Scalia will serve as the D. and L. Straus Distinguished Visiting Professor of 
Law. 
</P>
